Technological determinism is a concept that encompasses, pragmatically, a wide range of ideas, from the technological impulse or imperative to a strict sense of an underlying logic that there is driving force that drives the destiny of humanity and that relates to the laws of science and how they are embodied in technology.
Almost all interpretations of technological determinism have in common ideas two general ideas: that technological development in itself unfolds along a path independent of any cultural or political influence and that at the same time technology has "effects" on societies that are inherent and not socially conditional.
To give an example, one could argue that the existence of cars necessarily derive from the development of roads.
However, a national road network is not economically viable for a reduced volume of automobiles and new manufacturing techniques are being designed to reduce the cost of owning a vehicle.
Massive car use also generates an increased incidence in traffic accidents, leading to the development of new techniques in the health field to repair damaged bodies.
